Ad Text:
Brunel has partnered with a leading resources company on a contract opportunity for an Data Analyst. Ideal for a data analyst/data scientist with mining and telemetry experience who can turn complex operational data into trusted, actionable insights.

Description

This role delivers data models, analytics, and decision-support tools that improve safety, performance, and operational efficiency of a Collision Avoidance System across mining operations. You'll work across operational, sensor, and spatial datasets to support incident review, optimisation, and strategic decision making, partnering with operations, engineering, and technology teams to define metrics and embed data-driven practices.

Key outcomes:

Analytical models and data pipelines that are robust, accurate, maintainable, and trusted by stakeholders.
Predictive models and statistical analysis using spatial data for creating visualisations, reports and decision making.
Integrated, well-governed datasets combining sensor, geological, and operational data to support repeatable analysis and decision making.
Well-documented business cases and analytical findings that inform product, process, and technology decisions.

Key Responsibilities:

Apply statistical and machine learning techniques to analyse operational and sensor datasets; build predictive models to identify trends and anomalies.
Integrate diverse data sources (sensor, geological, operational) into reliable datasets for analysis and reporting.
Design algorithms that support optimisation and automation, working with developers on proof-of-concepts where needed.
Build dashboards and visualisations that make complex analysis easy to understand, partnering with UI/UX teams as required.
Run stakeholder workshops to gather requirements, identify opportunities, and support adoption of process improvements.
Work with architecture and delivery teams to map analytics impacts to solution requirements.
Partner with IT/data platform teams to ensure data security, integrity, and availability.
Drive continuous improvement by identifying where data can improve safety, productivity, and decision making.

Profile

Bachelor's degree in Computer Science, Statistics, or a related discipline.
Proven experience delivering data analytics/data science in an industrial environment, ideally mining.
Strong programming capability in Python (or Matlab/R).
Experience with geospatial tooling (e.g. ArcGIS or similar).
Experience with modern data platforms (Snowflake and AWS analytics services).
Experience with dashboards/visualisation tools (Power BI, Tableau, Grafana or similar).
Strong communication skills and a structured, detail-focused approach to data quality and documentation.
3+ years' experience in mining operations; knowledge of open pit mining (iron ore preferred).

Highly regarded:

Experience with telemetry and sensor datasets (V2X, heavy mobile equipment, or safety systems).
Familiarity with OT environments, mine control, or autonomy operations.
Experience working with large-scale IoT datasets and networks.
Background supporting safety analysis, incident investigations, or continuous improvement programs with data.
Exposure to production-grade data pipelines and cloud analytics tooling.

Job Offer

About Brunel:

Brunel is a recruitment and flexible workforce solution provider which connects talented people with opportunities throughout Australasia and around the world. We specialise in highly skilled roles across a variety of technical, professional, trades and craft disciplines, pairing candidates with industry-leading projects and organisations on a contract, permanent or secondment basis.

Operating in Australasia since 1997, Brunel has major bases of operation in Perth, Sydney, Brisbane and Port Moresby, which are further backed by the strength and reach of a truly global network spanning over 45 countries, 120 offices and 45 years of successful operation.

Brunel is proud to be equal opportunity employer and encourages applications from Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander and female candidates.

If you meet the above requirements and would like to be considered for this role, please submit your interest using the 'Apply' button. Applying is quick and easy - just make sure you have the following documents ready to go:

Resume

Ad Text:
Location: Sydney (4 days in office, 1-day WFH)
Reports to: Technical Operations Director, APAC
Department: Global Technical Operations
Salary: $180,000 + super + bonus


The Opportunity:

A leading music organisation is now growing their Global Technical Operations hub in Sydney and looking for a Service Reliability Engineer (SRE) to join their team.

This is more than a traditional ops role - it's an opportunity to bring a software engineering mindset to reliability, automation, and scalability in a global, high-impact environment.

What You'll Do:

You'll join a collaborative, hands-on team responsible for the stability, performance, and scalability of global platforms. Working closely with development, infrastructure, and security teams, you'll help build a resilient environment that keeps music flowing - from studio tools to streaming systems.




Design and maintain high-availability, high-performance systems for global applications.
Automate everything - from infrastructure provisioning to deployment and scaling - using tools like Terraform, Ansible, and Python.
Build robust monitoring and observability frameworks with AWS CloudWatch, Dynatrace, Prometheus, Grafana, or Splunk.
Optimize CI/CD pipelines to improve reliability and deployment speed.
Participate in on-call rotations, troubleshoot incidents, and lead post-incident reviews.
Champion SRE principles - embed SLOs, SLIs, and error budgets into everyday engineering.
Collaborate across Dev, Infra, and Security teams to create a culture of continuous improvement and reliability.

About You

You're a technically strong and level-headed engineer who loves automation, thrives in complex environments, and knows how to balance pragmatism with perfection.




Background in systems administration (Linux/Windows) in a large-scale environment.
Proficient in at least one programming language (Python, Go, or Java).
Hands-on experience with AWS (GCP or Azure a bonus).
Deep understanding of networking, containers (Docker/Kubernetes), and Infrastructure as Code (Terraform, Ansible).
Experience with monitoring and observability tools such as Dynatrace, Prometheus, Grafana, or Datadog.
Calm, collaborative communicator with strong analytical and problem-solving skills.

Bonus Points For:




Experience with ServiceNow or ITIL processes.
Knowledge of chaos engineering, resilience testing, or advanced capacity planning.
Previous experience managing distributed, global systems in production.

Culture & Perks




Annual bonus $
Global collaboration and career growth opportunities

Interested?
Apply now or contact Sophia Parrelli at Talent International for a confidential chat.

Brunel has partnered with a leading resources company on a contract opportunity for an Embedded Developer. This role suits someone with collision avoidance systems experience who can deliver safety-critical, production-grade software for real-time environments.

Description

This role will design, implement, and optimise safety-critical decision-making software that prevents collisions across heavy mobile equipment. Working within a cross-functional autonomy squad, you'll deliver production-grade C/C++ components that integrate sensors, localisation, mapping, and control to ensure reliable fail-operational behaviour in dynamic, mixed-traffic environments.

Key Responsibilities:

Build collision avoidance components with a focus on performance, safety, modularity, testability, observability, and redundancy.
Uplift an existing codebase to production standard, including compliance with MISRA or similar guidelines.
Analyse field data and telemetry to scope and deliver new features that improve real-world performance.
Produce and maintain technical design documentation, safety cases, interface specifications, and operational guidance.
Perform hazard analysis and FMEA, and develop and validate safety-related functions and diagnostics.
Lead reviews of requirements and architecture, defining clear component boundaries and interfaces.
Run code, design, and test reviews to meet coding standards, safety requirements, and established practices.
Create and maintain unit, integration, HIL, and simulation-based tests, including regression suites for edge cases and collision scenarios.
Support field triage and root-cause resolution using logs, telemetry, and simulation reproductions.
Mentor engineers in modern C/C++, safe concurrency, numerical robustness, and data-driven validation.

Profile

3+ years' experience delivering real-time or near real-time systems in C/C++.
Experience across collision avoidance, motion planning, or ADAS, including control integration.
Strong modelling capability for control and planning (kinematic/dynamic models, constraints, feasibility).
Modern C++ (C++17+), performance optimisation, and strong engineering workflows (CMake, Docker, Git/PRs/CI).
Linux and networking fundamentals, plus observability practices (metrics, tracing, structured logs).
Safety-critical development experience, including safety mechanisms, watchdogs, and degraded modes.
Familiarity with standards such as MISRA/AUTOSAR and static analysis tooling.
Experience with DDS and/or ROS 2 in distributed systems (QoS, message schemas, lifecycle nodes).
Ability to scope work and estimate effort accurately.

Highly regarded:

V2X / DSRC communications experience.
Data-driven collision avoidance, PID control, brake control algorithms.
GPS/GNSS experience.
Embedded software delivery in production environments (mining, automotive, rail).

Elastic Observability Engineer – Telco Client | 6–12 Month Daily Contract | Sydney (Hybrid)

We are seeking an experienced Elastic Observability Engineer to design, implement, and operate an enterprise-scale observability platform using the Elastic Stack (Elasticsearch, Kibana, Elastic Observability).

The role delivers end-to-end observability across hybrid and cloud environments, covering logs, metrics, traces, uptime, and APM, enabling faster incident detection and root-cause analysis.

You’ll work closely with SRE, DevOps, Platform, and Application teams to onboard services, define standards, and improve observability maturity.

Responsibilities:

Deploy and operate Elastic Observability platform (Elasticsearch, Kibana, Beats, Logstash, APM).
Ensure cluster performance, scalability, reliability, and high availability.
Build dashboards, alerts, and ingestion pipelines; troubleshoot performance issues.
Automate provisioning using IaC (Terraform, Ansible, Helm) and support Kubernetes/container deployments.
Collaborate with teams to onboard services, define observability standards, and optimize ILM, retention, and cost.
Requirements:

Hands-on Elastic Stack experience; Elasticsearch internals, indexing, performance tuning.
Kubernetes and cloud (AWS, Azure, GCP) experience; Linux, networking, distributed systems knowledge.
CI/CD, automation (Python/Bash). SRE/DevOps/Platform background.
Nice to Have:

Elastic Certified Observability Engineer, OpenTelemetry, enterprise/hybrid-cloud experience, ITSM tools (ServiceNow/PagerDuty).

John Holland Group is seeking Expressions of Interest from highly experienced Systems Engineers, from Engineering level to Systems Engineering Managers, to join our Rail Engineering & Integration group of specialist rail engineers, supporting the delivery of SESA services across our portfolio of upcoming and ongoing rail projects in Sydney and Melbourne. These roles will contribute to the delivery of complex, safety‑critical systems that underpin the performance, reliability, and regulatory compliance of our rail projects.

This opportunity can be based in our Sydney or Melbourne offices.

About the Opportunity:
We are looking to engage Systems Engineering professionals with demonstrated capability across the full systems engineering lifecycle to join our team. This is a long-term opportunity to join our SESA team where successful candidates will work within multi‑disciplinary engineering teams, supporting the development, integration, assurance, and verification of rail systems and subsystems.

This EOI aims to identify individuals who can provide expertise aligned with recognised rail standards, including but not limited to:

-EN 50126 / 50128 / 50129 (RAMS)
-Systems Engineering (ISO/IEC 15288)
-CENELEC standards for safety‑related systems
-Australian rail safety and accreditation frameworks

Key Responsibilities:

We are seeking Systems Engineers with strong capability across the structured engineering lifecycle with experience in the following Systems Engineering competencies:

Requirements Engineering
-Eliciting, analysing, validating, and managing system requirements
-Developing requirements baselines and ensuring traceability

System Architecture & Design
-Developing system architectures, functional models, and interface definitions
-Conducting functional decomposition and allocation of requirements

Interface Management
-Identifying, defining, and controlling internal and external interfaces
-Managing interface hazards, performance dependencies, and integration constraints

Verification & Validation (V&V)
-Preparing V&V strategies, plans, traceability matrices, and test evidence
-Executing and coordinating verification across multidisciplinary teams

Integration Planning & Coordination
-Sequencing integration activities and resolving integration issues
-Ensuring subsystem compatibility and alignment to the system architecture

Configuration & Change Management
-Applying disciplined SE control processes to manage baselines and technical change

Systems Assurance
-Supporting RAMS, hazard management, and compliance to applicable standards (e.g., EN 50126 series)
-Contributing to system safety cases and assurance artefacts

Lifecycle Management
-Applying the V Model and ISO/IEC 15288 principles across concept, development, test, and operational phases

Qualifications:
-Degree in Systems Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Mechatronics, Software, or related discipline
-Postgraduate qualifications in Systems Engineering (desirable)
-CSEP/ESEP certification (desirable)
-Rail‑specific safety competencies where relevant

The Opportunity

You’ll work hands-on with real-world energy data, contributing to cloud-based solar forecasting, wind resource assessment, and short-term power system modelling — all within a fast-moving, R&D-led environment.

This role suits either an enthusiastic graduate or someone with deeper experience. What matters most is curiosity, initiative, and the ability to learn quickly.

What You’ll Do

Build and maintain data engineering pipelines for renewable energy systems

Develop short-term energy forecasting models

Contribute to computer vision–based solar forecasting

Support wind sensing and power resource assessment platforms

Collaborate closely with engineers and researchers on cutting-edge R&D

Must-Have Skills

Strong Python programming

Competency in C/C++

Comfortable working in Linux environments

Demonstrated experience in data engineering or data science pipelines

Nice to Have

Machine learning or statistical modelling exposure

Experience with dynamic systems or numerical methods

Knowledge of energy markets (especially Australia’s NEM)

Strong communication skills

Qualifications

STEM degree (Computer Science, Engineering, Physics, Maths, Statistics, etc.)

Postgraduate study helpful but not required

We are seeking a Contract Senior Data Architect / Data Modeller to lead the design of a common enterprise data model supporting the migration of fragmented data assets from SAS NEO to a Databricks Lakehouse platform.

This role plays a critical part in establishing a unified, governed data foundation that standardises core entities, definitions, and relationships across the organisation, enabling scalable analytics, reporting, and AI/ML use cases.

You will work across architecture, data engineering, analytics, and business teams to rationalise existing schemas, translate embedded business logic, and define canonical domains aligned to modern Lakehouse and cloud data architecture principles.

Key Responsibilities
Design conceptual, logical, and physical data models supporting enterprise analytics and AI
Define canonical data domains, entities, and relationships
Map legacy SAS NEO datasets and unstructured sources to target Databricks models
Translate embedded business logic into governed, reusable data structures
Define OLTP, OLAP, and dimensional models (star/snowflake)
Establish metadata, lineage, and documentation standards
Ensure alignment with Lakehouse, ELT, and cloud architecture patterns
Collaborate with engineers, architects, and stakeholders on target-state design
Required Skills & Experience
Strong experience in Data Architecture, Data Modelling & Design
Proven migration experience to Databricks or Lakehouse platforms
Conceptual, logical and physical modelling expertise
Dimensional modelling (star/snowflake) and OLTP vs OLAP design
Advanced SQL
Experience with relational databases (SQL Server, Oracle, Postgres, MySQL, SAS)
Cloud platforms: Azure, AWS or GCP
Data integration & ETL/ELT design patterns
Metadata management, lineage, and governance frameworks
Nice to Have
Python, Scala, or Spark
Informatica, ADF, Talend, Boomi, SSIS
Kafka / Event Hubs / streaming
Power BI, Tableau, Qlik
MDM and data quality tooling
Infrastructure-as-code exposure (Terraform / ARM)
If you would like to hear more please APPLY below. Australian Citizens or PR only.

About us:

Metropolitan Memorial Parks is a NSW Government entity responsible for managing eight Memorial Parks across the Sydney and Hunter region. We're committed to providing genuine care and affordable choices for everyone, while expanding our services to meet the diverse needs of our communities.

About the role:

As our new Integration Solutions Specialist, you will play a pivotal role in designing, implementing, and maintaining system integrations across MMP’s enterprise platforms. You’ll ensure seamless data flow, support operational efficiency, and enable strategic decision-making through robust system connectivity.

Key responsibilities:

Collaborate with Head of Technology and IT leaders to develop integration architecture strategy and roadmap

Architect and implement integration solutions across platforms such as ERP, CRM, HRIS.

Develop and maintain APIs and ETL processes to support data exchange and interoperability.

Strong knowledge of integration technologies and standards (APIs, REST, SOAP, messaging, ESB, event streaming).

Hands-on experience with WebMethods (or equivalent platforms such as MuleSoft, Boomi, Azure Integration Services).

Provide expert-level diagnostics, troubleshooting, and performance tuning for integration-related issues.

Create and maintain comprehensive documentation for all integration points and architecture.

Ensure compliance with IT governance, privacy laws & change management frameworks.

Engage with stakeholders, including business analysts, developers & system owners.

Provide training and support to end-users and helpdesk teams.

Monitor integration performance and identify opportunities for optimisation

About you:

Proven experience in system integration across SaaS enterprise platforms

Strong understanding of API design, ETL processes, and data governance.

Familiarity with SaaS implementation and project lifecycle management.

Excellent problem-solving, communication, and stakeholder engagement skills.

Degree in Information Technology, Computer Science, or related field is desirable

Certifications in integration platforms or project management (e.g., PMP, ITIL) would be an advantage

Experience in cemetery and crematorium operations or government enterprise systems would be highly regarded

If you're a skilled integration professional looking for a new challenge, please submit your application, including your resume and cover letter, addressing the key responsibilities.

Salary: Up to $1000 p/d + super (may be negotiable)

 Primary Purpose of the Role Deliver scalable data pipelines and platform enhancements across Databricks and AWS, supporting the build of new enterprise data products. The role will apply medallion architecture, data mesh principles, and modern engineering practices.

About The Role

As a Data Scientist, you can expect every day to be different, but there are a few workflows that are consistent. In line with the expectations for each ASD level, you will be responsible for identifying suitable data sets and problems, as well as subsequently planning and performing analysis on a wide range of data. You will do this in accordance with our legislative, policy and ethical frameworks. 

In your role, you will be expected to liaise with both customers and engineers and will need to be able to explain the methods and results of your work to people with varying levels of data science experience. Continuous learning and a thirst for knowledge are expected as you maintain your knowledge of both our abilities and the state of the art possibilities, blending the best of what the data science community has on offer. You will need to work in a multi-disciplinary environment to deliver capabilities that allow ASD’s intelligence and cyber analysts to have the right information, provided in the right way at the right time. 

Further information can be found at: I’m changing my career | Australian Signals Directorate (asd.gov.au).




Key Duties:

ASD 4 Data Scientist

An ASD 4 Data Scientists, you will work to the broad direction of the executive leadership to perform and achieve complex data generation and analysis work within an integrated workforce. You will require knowledge of compliance with the legislative frameworks, government decision-making and an understanding of Australian Signals Directorate’s mission.

You will be deliberate with the learning of technical and analytical skills and proactive with communicating with their team and leadership. You will exercise sound decision-making to provide technical advice and in line with direction, will engage in complex problem solving to deliver data science solutions that affect strategic, political or operational outcomes for the Australian Signals Directorate.

You will positively contribute to building team capability and will be accountable to contribute towards ongoing self-improvement and professional development for their career. 




ASD 5 Data Scientist

An ASD 5 Data Scientist will work under limited direction to perform and achieve complex data generation and analysis work within an integrated workforce. You are accountable to have and maintain a well-developed understanding of compliance to relevant legislative frameworks, government decision-making and the Australian Signals Directorate’s mission and policy requirements.

You will be accountable for organising your workflow and making independent decisions relating to their area of responsibility. You will interpret and provide advice within the data function area based on legislation, policy and procedures. You will undertake research and analysis, conduct investigations and perform data generation and analysis work to achieve results.

You may coordinate and contribute to the work of a team and provide advice and assistance on methods of task completion to team members. You may be a team coach and are expected to be capable of reviewing and developing the quality of work undertaken by others and identifying opportunities for on-the-job training within a work unit.

As a Data Scientist, you will be required to engage and communicate with stakeholders to respond and provide advice on issues to mission outcomes. You will be accountable to contribute towards ongoing self-improvement and professional development.




ASD 6 Data Scientist

An ASD 6 Data Scientist is accountable, under the broad direction of the executive leadership, to perform and achieve complex to very complex data generation and analysis work within an integrated workforce. You will require knowledge of compliance with legislative frameworks, government decision-making and strong understanding of Australian Signals Directorate’s mission.

You will exercise a degree of independence and perform a subject matter expert role. You will exercise sound decision making and judgement to provide strong technical advice. Engage in complex to very complex problem solving and issue management and may coordinate and contribute to detailed or sensitive projects that impact on strategic, political or operational outcomes for the Australian Signals Directorate.

You may be a Line Manager and mentor, and will be accountable for the outcomes of the planning for work and performance goals. You are expected to be capable of building team capability through coaching, feedback and developing the quality of work undertaken by others within a work unit.

As a Data Scientist, you will be involved in key stakeholder relationships and will be required to identify relevant stakeholders’ expectations and concerns to develop and communicate methodologies and practices to achieve outcomes. You will be accountable to contribute towards ongoing self-improvement and professional development of their work area.  




About the Team

Data scientist roles within Mission Data Division (MDD) develops capabilities and data solutions to enable ASD mission areas, to support ASD and ADF mission requirements.

This is achieved through the delivery of data platforms, ensuring the data is fit for purpose, delivering bespoke mission tools and applications, and providing complex analytic support, including Machine Learning and Artificial Intelligence capability.

As part of your job, ASD will support you and provide opportunities to stay up-to-date with the latest trends and technologies to develop new ways to collect information and solve intelligence problems. The work we do is unique, critical and incredibly rewarding. 




Our Ideal Candidate

Our ideal candidate has a thirst for learning and an ability to convince data to tell its story. They can have industry experience, formal training or a particular domain expertise but regardless of this, they must have strong critical thinking and reasoning and be able to demonstrate this through the selection process. At the core of their skills is an understanding of the fundamentals of data or geospatial analysis and/or data science. Our ideal candidate embraces diversity and is willing to approach problems from a cross disciplinary perspective. They have strong interpersonal skills and the ability to ask the right questions. Most importantly, they need to enjoy working as part of a dynamic team to solve interesting problems.

ASD is seeking applicants to fill current and anticipated vacancies and to create a merit pool for future vacancies. In line with the Australian Public Service Commissioner’s Direction 2022, upon completion of the recruitment activity, the merit pool will be available to locations across Australia. 




Application Closing Date: Sunday, 1 March 2026




For further information, please review the Information Pack, reference ASD/00859/26 on www.asd.gov.au/careers.

You are accountable to have and maintain a well-developed understanding of compliance to relevant legislative frameworks, government decision-making and the Australian Signals Directorate’s mission and policy requirements.

You will be accountable for organising your workflow and making independent decisions relating to their area of responsibility. You will interpret and provide advice within the data function area based on legislation, policy and procedures. You will undertake research and analysis, conduct investigations and perform data generation and analysis work to achieve results.

You may coordinate and contribute to the work of a team and provide advice and assistance on methods of task completion to team members. You may be a team coach and are expected to be capable of reviewing and developing the quality of work undertaken by others and identifying opportunities for on-the-job training within a work unit.

As a Data Scientist, you will be required to engage and communicate with stakeholders to respond and provide advice on issues to mission outcomes. You will be accountable to contribute towards ongoing self-improvement and professional development.




ASD 6 Data Scientist

An ASD 6 Data Scientist is accountable, under the broad direction of the executive leadership, to perform and achieve complex to very complex data generation and analysis work within an integrated workforce. You will require knowledge of compliance with legislative frameworks, government decision-making and strong understanding of Australian Signals Directorate’s mission.

You will exercise a degree of independence and perform a subject matter expert role. You will exercise sound decision making and judgement to provide strong technical advice. Engage in complex to very complex problem solving and issue management and may coordinate and contribute to detailed or sensitive projects that impact on strategic, political or operational outcomes for the Australian Signals Directorate.

You may be a Line Manager and mentor, and will be accountable for the outcomes of the planning for work and performance goals. You are expected to be capable of building team capability through coaching, feedback and developing the quality of work undertaken by others within a work unit.

As a Data Scientist, you will be involved in key stakeholder relationships and will be required to identify relevant stakeholders’ expectations and concerns to develop and communicate methodologies and practices to achieve outcomes. You will be accountable to contribute towards ongoing self-improvement and professional development of their work area.  




About the Team

Data scientist roles within Mission Data Division (MDD) develops capabilities and data solutions to enable ASD mission areas, to support ASD and ADF mission requirements.

This is achieved through the delivery of data platforms, ensuring the data is fit for purpose, delivering bespoke mission tools and applications, and providing complex analytic support, including Machine Learning and Artificial Intelligence capability.

As part of your job, ASD will support you and provide opportunities to stay up-to-date with the latest trends and technologies to develop new ways to collect information and solve intelligence problems. The work we do is unique, critical and incredibly rewarding. 




Our Ideal Candidate

Our ideal candidate has a thirst for learning and an ability to convince data to tell its story. They can have industry experience, formal training or a particular domain expertise but regardless of this, they must have strong critical thinking and reasoning and be able to demonstrate this through the selection process. At the core of their skills is an understanding of the fundamentals of data or geospatial analysis and/or data science. Our ideal candidate embraces diversity and is willing to approach problems from a cross disciplinary perspective. They have strong interpersonal skills and the ability to ask the right questions. Most importantly, they need to enjoy working as part of a dynamic team to solve interesting problems.

ASD is seeking applicants to fill current and anticipated vacancies and to create a merit pool for future vacancies. In line with the Australian Public Service Commissioner’s Direction 2022, upon completion of the recruitment activity, the merit pool will be available to locations across Australia. 




Application Closing Date: Sunday, 1 March 2026




For further information, please review the Information Pack, reference ASD/00859/26 on www.asd.gov.au/careers.

Who We Are

 

iSelect and Compare the Market are trusted, well-known brands dedicated to helping millions of Australians compare and buy personal finance and household products such as insurance, energy, and loans. Together, we provide a seamless, customer-focused experience that makes it easier for Australians to find the right products to suit their needs.

 

What You’ll Be Doing

 

• Manage and optimise observability platforms, especially New Relic
• Build and maintain dashboards, visualisations, and service insights
• Implement observability tooling using Terraform and other IaC practices
• Partner with engineering teams to improve instrumentation and distributed tracing
• Enhance alert quality, support incident root cause analysis, and evaluate new observability capabilities

                                                                                                                                        

 

What’s In It For You

 

At Compare the Market and iSelect, we’re all about helping people make smart choices – and joining us might just be yours.  We offer an environment where your ideas are heard, your contributions are valued, and your growth genuinely matters. Collaboration is part of our DNA, and you’ll be joining a supportive, forward-thinking team where you can do meaningful work (and be recognised for it!) 

 

We’re guided by three shared values that shape how we work, how we treat each other, and how we show up for our customers - Drive, Noble Intent and All Together.

 

Plus, we offer a range of great perks to help you thrive both in and out of work:

 

Vibrant and social community who have annual celebrations, family fun days and regular events
Enjoy flexible work arrangements, including the option of one day working from home each week or a 9-day fortnight
Enjoy additional leave days - ‘ME’ leave and ‘Volunteer Day’ leave
Option to purchase additional leave
Return To Work bonus for returning parents
Quarterly Award and Recognition program

 

 

What Sets You Apart

 

We’d love to hear from professionals who have…..

• Strong understanding of observability concepts—metrics, logs, traces, distributed tracing, service maps
• Hands-on experience with New Relic or similar tools (Datadog, Grafana, Prometheus, Dynatrace)
• Experience building dashboards, alert policies, and instrumentation
• Exposure to Terraform, scripting/automation, and cloud/container environments (Kubernetes, Docker)
• Familiarity with OpenTelemetry, SRE practices (SLIs/SLOs), CI/CD pipelines, and logging platforms would be desireable

 

 

 

Sound like a good fit? Let’s talk.

 

 

At Compare the Market and iSelect we’re proud to be an Equal Opportunity Employer and we embrace diversity.  

 

This role is available to candidates with unlimited Australian working rights only. Sponsorship is not available.  

 

Compare the Market and iSelect are committed to protecting your privacy. All applications and personal information are kept confidential and securely stored in line with Australian privacy laws, used only for recruitment purposes, and not shared with third parties outside the Auto and General Holdings Group without your consent.

Company description:



The NSW Department of Education is the largest provider of public education in Australia with responsibility for delivering high-quality public education to two-thirds of the NSW student population. For more information about the NSW Department of Education, please visit https://education.nsw.gov.au/



Job description:



At the NSW Department of Education, we educate and inspire lifelong learners - from early childhood, through schooling to vocational education and training.

Ongoing Full-Time opportunity to make impactful transformative service improvement
Located in Parramatta with flexible working arrangements available
Salary ranges from $129,464 to $142,665 p.a. plus superannuation and annual leave loading

About Us

The Intelligent Automation Team within the NSW Department of Education is a mature automation practice that has developed extensive robotic process automation (RPA) capabilities using Blue Prism as its core RPA tool, alongside Microsoft Power Platform solutions. The team operates within the Shared Services Directorate, which is responsible for transforming how we deliver services to our customers.

We are a group of passionate professionals committed to delivering high-quality services. Our team has a proven track record of successfully developing and implementing RPA solutions that streamline internal processes and enhance service delivery.

About the role

As the Lead Automation Developer, you will be responsible for leading a team of high-performing developers to identify, build and deliver automated solutions. Working in an agile environment your responsibilities will include:

Engaging with stakeholders and leading the discovery and delivery of high-quality solutions
Leading process discovery to identify and assess automation opportunities that improves operational effectiveness
Ensuring automation solutions are effective and aligned with regulatory requirements and best practices.
Build automation capability across the Department, by guiding stakeholders to support adoption of Intelligent automation.

For further information please click here to view the role description

About you

You are a driven and innovative Lead Automation Developer with proven industry experience delivering intelligent automation solutions. You bring strong technical leadership and architectural expertise across the full automation lifecycle, from design through to implementation and quality assurance.

The ideal candidate will demonstrate:

A minimum of 3 years' experience in end-to-end lifecycle implementation of automation technologies, including Robotic Process Automation (RPA) tools such as Blue Prism or equivalent tools, Low-code platforms, Microsoft Power Platform, or Cognitive Automation - with expertise in AI and ML technologies (Certifications are a plus)
Exceptional stakeholder management and presentation skills with the confidence to engage with our Senior Leadership team
Solid understanding of Blue Prism Infrastructure and Robotic Operating Model (ROM)
Solid understanding of technology and architecture concepts, including OCR, AI, chatbots, virtual agents, and human-in-the-loop/attended automation tools
Strong analytical and problem-solving capabilities.
Strong logical reasoning and solutions ideation skills

Key Knowledge and Experience

Knowledge of and commitment to implementing the Department's Aboriginal Education Policy and upholding the Department's Partnership Agreement with the NSW AECG and to ensure quality outcomes for Aboriginal people.

Essential requirements of the role

Tertiary qualifications in IT, Computer Science, Business or a related discipline and/or demonstrated equivalent professional experience.
Demonstrated understanding of and commitment to the value of public education.

Benefits

Flexible working arrangements
35 hour working week
Competitive salary, salary sacrificing, employer's contribution to superannuation and annual leave loading
Flex Leave entitlements, generous holidays & leave conditions
Opportunities for advancement and mobility across the Department to support your career growth

How to apply

Attach a resume (maximum 5 pages) and a cover letter (maximum 2 pages) outlining how you meet the requirements and capabilities of this role, as well as providing answers to the pre-screening question below:

Question:

Describe a time you achieved stakeholder support where there was resistance to an automation initiative. What was the reason for the resistance, how did you approach it and what was the result? (max 350 words)

Applicants are encouraged to prepare their application materials independently. The selection panel values authentic and personally written responses that reflect your own experience, insights and alignment with the Department's values and priorities.

Please refer to the Applicant's Guide to Applying to assist you with your application.

If you are an existing Education Support Staff (corporate staff) with the NSW Department of Education, click here for instructions on how to submit your application.

All other applicants please submit your application by clicking ‘Apply Now'.


Note: the selection process will include a range of assessment techniques to assist in determining your suitability for the role. Successful candidates will be required to undertake pre-employment screening for this role which includes a National Criminal History Check.

As a condition of employment, successful candidates not currently employed by the Department must provide a valid Working with Children Check (WWCC) clearance number. Renewal is not required after the WWCC expires, as long as you remain in a non-child-related role. Employer obligations only apply while the WWCC is valid.

Candidates must have Australian work rights (citizens, permanent residents, New Zealand citizens or a valid work visa). Ongoing (permanent) roles are open to Australian citizens and permanent residents and New Zealand citizens, while temporary roles welcome applicants with a visa.


Closing date: Friday 27 February 2025 at 11:59pm.


For role enquiries please contact Neelu Choudhury at neelakshi.choudhury@det.nsw.edu.au and for recruitment process enquiries please contact Jenny Nguyen at jenny.nguyen199@det.nsw.edu.au


We welcome applications from all ages and genders, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, culturally and linguistically diverse groups, the LGBTQIA+ community, veterans, refugees and people with disability. If we can make some adjustments to our recruitment/interview process to better enable you to shine, please contact the Diversity and Inclusion Team (youbelong@det.nsw.edu.au) or visit NSW Department of Education Diversity and Inclusion.


A recruitment pool may be created through this recruitment process. A recruitment pool is a group of applicants who have been assessed and identified as suitable for this role, and who may be considered for a range of similar roles, including temporary, term or ongoing roles, over the next 18 months.

Ad Text:
Level 3 Engineer (MSP)

Location: Sydney (hybrid)
Salary: $120,000 – $140,000 + Super (+ performance based bonus)

About the Role:
As a Data Engineer, you will design, build, and optimise enterprise-scale data solutions, helping our clients unlock the value of their data and accelerate performance. This role blends hands-on technical delivery with client-facing consulting, giving you the opportunity to shape scalable solutions using Databricks, cloud platforms, and modern data engineering practices. You’ll play a key role in building DyFlex’s emerging Data and AI capability, ensuring our clients achieve meaningful business outcomes through innovative data solutions.

Your tasks and responsibilities:

Build and maintain scalable data pipelines for ingesting, transforming, and delivering data
Manage and optimise databases, warehouses, and cloud storage solutions

Strong proficiency in Python and SQL; experience with at least one additional language (e.g. Java, Typescript/Javascript)
Experience with modern frameworks such as Apache Spark, Airflow, dbt, Kafka, or Flink
Background in building ML pipelines, MLOps practices, or feature stores is highly valued
Proven expertise in relational databases, data modelling, and query optimisation
Demonstrated ability to solve complex technical problems independently
Excellent communication skills with ability to engage clients and stakeholders
Degree in Computer Science, Engineering, Data Science, Mathematics, or a related field

What we offer:

Work with SAP’s latest technologies on cloud as S/4HANA, BTP and Joule, plus Databricks, ML/AI tools and cloud platforms
A flexible and supportive work environment including work from home
Competitive remuneration and benefits including novated lease, birthday leave, remote working, additional purchased leave, and company-provided laptop
Competitive remuneration and benefits including novated lease, birthday leave, salary packaging, wellbeing programme, additional purchased leave, and company-provided laptop Comprehensive training budget and paid certifications (Databricks, SAP, cloud platforms)
Structured career advancement pathways with mentoring from senior engineers
Exposure to diverse industries and client environments

Join a renowned organisation delivering projects to some of Australia’s leading enterprises

DyFlex is committed to providing a safe, flexible and respectful environment for staff free from all forms of discrimination, bullying and harassment. Please note that we can’t offer sponsorship for this role and we expect a clear statement about your legal rights in Australia, especially if you are applying from overseas.

Job Title: Senior Machine Learning Engineer - Learning Experience
Ad Text:
Company Description


Join the team redefining how the world experiences design.

Hey, g'day, mabuhay, kia ora,你好, hallo, vítejte!

Thanks for stopping by. We know job hunting can be a little time consuming and you're probably keen to find out what's on offer, so we'll get straight to the point. 

Where and how you can work

Our flagship campus is in Sydney, with a second campus in Melbourne and co-working spaces in Brisbane, Perth, Adelaide, and Auckland, NZ. You have flexibility in how and where you work — whether that's from one of our spaces, from home, or a mix of both. This role is remote-friendly within Australia or New Zealand, so you can choose the setup that empowers you and your team to do your best work.

Job Description


About the Group/Team

This year, the Learning Experience group's mission is to ignite creativity in every learner by being fun and accessible, saving teachers and course creators time, and looking after every learner, whether in school, on campus, or in the workplace. We want to continue evolving Canva into a best-in-class learning tool, so that we have a sticky product with better retention.

In 2026, our Engaging Learning team is making it dramatically easier for teachers to save time through two core capabilities: discovering curriculum-aligned content that's ready to use in the classroom, and AI workflows tailored to their specific teaching tasks. We're building discovery systems that surface the right content for each teacher's curriculum context, and generation capabilities that understand educational standards while integrating seamlessly into their existing workflows.

About the Role/Specialty

We’re the Learning Experience group within Teams and Education, on a mission to ignite creativity in every learner. We’re building seamless learning pathways for users of all kinds—students, teachers, teams—across the globe. We thrive at the intersection of education and technology, driving impact by building experiences that empower learners to grow through Canva.

What you’ll do (responsibilities)

You’ll build, test, and ship ML-powered features that enhance learning experiences

You’ll design scalable ML pipelines in collaboration with our platform teams

You’ll work closely with PMs, designers and engineers to align on user needs and product direction

You’ll run experiments to validate assumptions and improve model effectiveness

You’ll contribute to shared ML infrastructure and best practices at Canva

You’ll keep up with state-of-the-art developments and explore ways to apply them at scale

What we're looking for

You're a highly skilled machine learning engineer with a proven track record of delivering ML-powered product features in production. You bring deep technical expertise across the ML lifecycle—from data wrangling and model development to evaluation, deployment, and monitoring. You're comfortable operating independently while collaborating deeply with cross-functional teams, and you're motivated by user impact and product outcomes.

Demonstrated experience building and deploying ML-powered features in production environments

Proficiency with Python and frameworks like TensorFlow or PyTorch

Skilled across the ML lifecycle: data processing, model training, evaluation, deployment, and monitoring

Proven ability to work independently while collaborating cross-functionally with product, design, and data

Experience with Generative AI (GenAI): LLMs, diffusion models, prompt engineering, RAG, or fine-tuning

Familiarity with GenAI platforms (e.g. OpenAI, Hugging Face, Anthropic) and embedding-based systems

Strong product mindset – prioritises ML solutions that improve user experience and product outcomes

Committed to scalable, maintainable ML systems with clear metrics and impact tracking

Passionate about ethical ML and responsible data usage, especially in learning environments

Enjoys mentoring and sharing best practices within the team

Additional Information


Don't tick all the boxes? Don't worry about that - nobody does!  

We’d still love to hear from you! At Canva, we know that great engineers come from a variety of backgrounds, and we value passion, curiosity, and a willingness to learn just as much as specific experience. If you're excited about this role but don’t tick every box, we encourage you to apply, you might a great fit in ways you didn’t expect!

What's in it for you?

Achieving our crazy big goals motivates us to work hard - and we do - but you'll experience lots of moments of magic, connectivity and fun woven throughout life at Canva, too. We also offer a stack of benefits to set you up for every success in and outside of work.

Here's a taste of what's on offer:

Equity packages - we want our success to be yours too
Inclusive parental leave policy that supports all parents & carers
An annual Vibe & Thrive allowance to support your wellbeing, social connection, office setup & more
Flexible leave options that empower you to be a force for good, take time to recharge and supports you personally

Check out  lifeatcanva.com for more info.

Other stuff to know

We make hiring decisions based on your experience, skills and passion, as well as how you can enhance Canva and our culture. When you apply, please tell us the pronouns you use and any reasonable adjustments you may need during the interview process.

Our flagship campus is in Sydney. This role is preferred to be based out of our Sydney office, where the majority of this team is located. 

Job Description


About the Group/Team

Canva Research – Design Generation

We’re building the systems that turn imagination into reality. Within Canva Research, the Design Generation group focuses on creating AI models and pipelines that produce beautiful designs for Canvas users. We work at the intersection of research and product, partnering closely with Product, Design, and Engineering to ship AI-powered experiences that feel magical, reliable, and deeply human. Our work directly shapes how users create, explore, and express ideas in Canva every day.

About the Role/Specialty:

As a Senior Research Engineer, we sit at the boundary between research and production. We explore new ideas in generative modelling, evaluate their real-world impact, and turn promising research into scalable systems that power Canva’s design experiences. As a Senior Research Engineer, this role operates with a high degree of autonomy, solving complex problems, influencing technical direction, and collaborating across teams to deliver meaningful outcomes. Our success is measured not just by research quality, but by the impact our work has on real users.

What you’ll do (responsibilities):

You’ll design, experiment with, and evaluate generative AI models for design-focused use cases.

You’ll translate research outcomes into scalable, production-ready systems.

You’ll collaborate closely with Product, Design, and Engineering partners to align research with user needs.

You’ll analyse model performance using both quantitative metrics and qualitative user signals.

You’ll contribute to technical discussions, architecture decisions, and long-term AI strategy.

You’ll share learnings through documentation, reviews, and internal presentations to uplift the broader team.

What we're looking for:


You’re an accomplished applied researcher who loves seeing ideas land in the hands of real users. You’re comfortable navigating ambiguity, balancing research depth with practical constraints, and making thoughtful trade-offs. You bring solid experience in machine learning or generative modelling, enjoy collaborating across disciplines, and care deeply about quality, ethics, and impact. You’re motivated by solving meaningful problems at scale and excited by the challenge of building AI that empowers creativity.

Bachelor or Masters degree in Computer Science, Computer Engineering or a related field, or equivalent skills gained through 3-5 years of work experience. Advanced qualifications including a PhD are an advantage.

Experience with generative models: Proficient in working with large language models (LLMs), diffusion models, and multimodal architectures to develop innovative solutions.

Skills in training generative models: Experienced in techniques such as fine-tuning, in-context learning, and reinforcement learning to optimise model performance.

Proficiency in deep learning frameworks: Skilled in leveraging tools like PyTorch, JAX, and HuggingFace for advanced research and experimentation.

Expertise in experimental design and evaluation: Capable of implementing experimental design strategies for generative models, using both quantitative metrics and qualitative analysis to assess outcomes.

Ability to enhance research tooling and workflows: Experienced in rapid prototyping, conducting ablation studies, and tracking experiments to streamline research processes.

Competence in data curation and analysis: Adept at managing and analysing datasets for training and evaluating generative systems.

Familiarity with current research literature: Skilled at reproducing impactful papers and applying novel techniques to address emerging problem spaces.
